http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Every educator has opportunities to enhance and enrich learning through the arts. These dance standards may be taught concurrently within other disciplines, without sacrificing time, while energizing the curriculum. Empowering students to move in many and varied arenas affords them opportunities for success in life. To have control of ones body enables one to have control of his or her life.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/rightsHolder.value: North Dakota Department of Public Instruction

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Movement Elements
Students understand movement elements and skills in dance.
Use dance elements to expand movement experiences.
Know boundaries of space.
Understand the characteristics of nonlocomotor/axial movements.
Understand the characteristics of locomotor movements in many directions and pathways.
Move to a rhythmic accompaniment and respond to changes in tempo.
Understand the characteristics of balance and proper alignment.
Understand how body parts and joints are used in movement.
Use kinesthetic awareness, concentration, and focus in performing movement skills.
Understand the characteristics of various dance movements and the underlying principles common to all movement.
Know basic dance steps, body positions, and spatial patterns for dances from various styles or traditions.
Understand the process of transferring a spatial pattern from the visual to the kinesthetic.
Understand the process of transferring a rhythmic pattern from auditory to kinesthetic.
Know a range of dynamics/movement qualities.
Use kinesthetic awareness, concentration, and focus in performing movement skills.
Use dance vocabulary to describe the action and movement elements in a dance.
Use appropriate technique in dance.
Know complex steps and patterns from various dance styles and traditions.
Understand the importance of using various complex time elements.
Understand the principles governing combinations and variations in a broad, dynamic range.
Understand why it is important to project in dance.
Choreography
Students understand choreographic principles processes and structures.
Understand the characteristics of a movement sequence.
Understand how improvisation is used to discover and invent movement.
Understand the characteristics of a dance phrase that is repeated and/or varied.
Know how to use the characteristics of solo and group dance to create whole compositions.
Understand the relationship of principles of creative design to dance.
Understand the significance of the processes of reordering and chance.
Understand the importance of dance structures or forms.
Understand the importance of working cooperatively in a small group during the choreographic process.
Know partner dance skills.
Know performance etiquette and stage terms.
Understand the importance of structures and forms of movement.
Understand the use of improvisation to generate movement.
Dance and Meaning
Students understand dance as a way to create and communicate meaning.
Communicate ideas using movement.
Know how dance is similar to and different from other forms of movement.
Understand the difference between pantomiming and miming.
Understand how different accompaniments can affect the meaning of dance.
Communicate feelings, ideas, and needs through dance.
Understand how movement choices are used to relate to abstract ideas and themes in dance.
Understand how interpretation of dance can be influenced by personal experience.
Dance and Thinking Skills
Students apply critical and creative thinking skills in dance.
Know that a variety of solutions can be used to solve movement problems.
Understand how various dances are similar to and different from one another.
Solve movement problems.
Know the critical elements that contribute to a dance in terms of space, time, and force.
Know the possible aesthetic criteria for evaluating dance.
Establish a set of aesthetic criteria for evaluation.
Formulate and answer aesthetic questions.
Dance, History, and Culture
Students understand the historical development of dance and its relationship to various cultures.
Know the characteristics of multicultural dance forms.
Understand the role and purpose of dance in various cultures.
Know characteristics of the forms of theatre dance.
Know and apply proper audience etiquette.
Know dances unique to own geographic region.
Know the similarities and differences in steps and movement styles from various cultures.
Know social and theatrical dances from a broad spectrum of 20th Century America.
Know the role of dance in various cultures and time periods.
Know appropriate audience response to dance performances.
Know the similarities and differences among various contemporary theatrical forms of dance.
Know dance pioneers as an index to the artistic and social values of civilization.
Understand how dance and dancers are portrayed in contemporary media.
Know the traditions and techniques of classical dance forms.
Dance and Personal Wellness
Students understand the connection between dance and personal wellness.
Know healthy practices that enhance the ability to dance.
Understand the importance of preparation and care of the body for dance.
Know strategies to prevent dance injuries.
Understand the value of personal health goals for dance improvement.
Know how lifestyle choices affect dancers.
Understand the significance of historical and cultural images of the body in dance.
Dance and Other Disciplines
Students understand the connections between dance and other disciplines.
Know how to use dance concepts in other disciplines.
Know how various dance concepts and principles relate to other disciplines.
Know the aesthetic impact of performance.
Know how dance is similar to and different from other disciplines.
Know how technology can be used to reinforce, enhance, or alter dances.
